-- t12. Obnoxious Satan: Milton, Neo-Roman Justice, and the Burden of Grace / rStevens, Paul -- tContributors -- tIndex  aTaking Exception to the Law explores how a range of early modern English writings responded to injustices perpetrated by legal procedures, discourses, and institutions. From canonical poems and plays to crime pamphlets and educational treatises, the essays engage with the relevance and wide appeal of legal questions in order to understand how literature operated in the early modern period.Justice in its many forms - legal, poetic, divine, natural, and customary - is examined through insightful and innovative analyses of a number of texts, including The Merchant of Venice, The Faerie Queene, and Paradise Lost. A major contribution to the growing field of law and literature, this collection offers cultural contexts, interpretive insights, and formal implications for the entire field of English Renaissance culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aLaw and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aLaw and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aLaw in literature. 7aDRAMA / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aBeecher, Donald, eeditor.1 aDeCook, Travis, eeditor.1 aWallace, Andrew, eeditor.1 aWilliams, Grant, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2015z9783110438673oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniver